Data Extraction from Google Maps API:

Overview:

  • The Google Web Services API is divided into multiple subsequent APIs each responsible for offering unique features.

    • Directions: calculates directions between locations in an optimized manner. Allows multiple waypoints (places to visit before reaching destination) as well as multiple routes ,modes of travel and traffic model.

    • Distance Matrix: provides travel distance and time for origin and destination pairs. Provide parameters to control what to avoid (highway, tolls), mode of travel, traffic model etc.

    • Elevation: provides elevation data for points.

    • Geocoding: provides geocoding and reverse geocoding. From address to lat/lng pairs and vice versa.

    • Roads: snaps points of travel to closest road and provide closest road to points , speed limits, tracking is only for premium users.

    • Time Zone: provides time zone information about a location.

    • Places: Include multiple functionalities.

      • Places search: allows for search of locations nearby to the provided location, the search can be modified via ranking by distance, price, opening now etc.

      • Place details: using a place_id, more detailed information regarding the place such as rating, address, phone number can be returned.

      • Place photos: allows the user to obtain google server photos for a location.

      • Place autocomplete: allows for autocomplete of a incomplete place text.

    • Geolocation: returns a location and accuracy radius based on information about cell towers and WiFi nodes that the mobile client can detect.

  • Please refer to the developer documentation for each web service API under the developers guide option. Google does an amazing job explaining the full functionality of each web service and provides ample examples.

    • Google Maps APIs often includes biasing of search query results to favor conditions met by parameters.

    • It is relatively easy to extract information for a list of points by separating via | or ,.

  • All API requests can be made using a HTTP GET request.

    • Example format: https:maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/{API Service Name}/{return format: json or xml}?{query}

    • Example request example: https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/directions/json?origin=Disneyland&destination=Universal+Studios+Hollywood4&key=YOUR_API_KEY

  • An access key is required and there are quotas restricting access.
    • Each web service API have different free usage limits under the policy and terms of the guide.

  • An premium account is available for purchase which allows access to more functionality and more quota. However, the free access keys are sufficient for most purposes.

  • Similar to other APIs, each object in Google Maps also includes its own Id.

Rate Limit:

  • Rate Limit Table

  • The rate limit information for each web service is also specified under its developer documentation under policies and usage.

  • The dashboard under the google API console provides the usage information for your application.

  • Quick Summary:

    • Geocoding API: 2500 requests per 24 hours as combination of server and client side queries. A limit rate of 50 requests per second.

    • Places API: 1000 requests per 24 hours as combination of server and client side queries.
      • maximum limit for free usage is 150,000 requests per 24 hour period if billing is enabled.

    • Elevation API: 2500 free requests as a sum of server and client. 512 locations per request. Up to 50 requests per second.

    • Directions API: 2500 free requests per day, as a sum of server and client. Up to 23 waypoints per request. 50 requests per second.

    • Roads API: 2500 free requests per 24 hours. Up to 100 points per request. 50 requests per second. No speed limit information.

    • Time Zone API: 2500 free requests per 24 hours. 50 requests per second.

    • Geolocation API: 2500 free requests per 24 hours. 50 requests per second.

    • Distance API

First Thoughts:

  • Google Maps API does an amazing job reporting geographical location and makes it easy to access the data. The main difficulty will be parsing the JSON/XML response from the sever.

  • It is recommended to use Google Maps API to supplement existing geographical data to perform analysis. It will be more useful to use google Maps to provide visualizations within R.

Visualizing:

Overview:

  • There are many packages in R to help with visualization of geographical location data. The following is a few of the useful packages:
    • ggplot2: provides an interface to simplify plotting of data and helps to visualize geographical data.
    • tmap: Allows flexible and interactive functions to produce thematic maps.
    • ggmap: Provides an easy way to overlay static maps from google Maps and other sites to visualize data.
    • leaflet: R version of the popular JavaScript library. This is used to create interactive maps.
    • SP Package: This package is one of the fundamental packages in R that deals with spatial data. It was observed that many of the packages references back to the SP package.

Leaflet:

  • The Visualization section of the report will mainly focus on using the leaflet package. It appears that leaflet package offers the most flexibility and customizability for visualization.

  • The down side is that this can only be loaded via connection to the internet.

  • Since this package works with html and javascript in its underlying structure. The interactive maps can not be displayed in PDF format.

Example 2: Showing Some Google Map Outputs:

  • Goal: Tracing the directions from Work to an apartment, showing places of interest around these locations with appropriate labels.

Functions

  • Polyline
    • A polyline is a list of lat/lng pairs compressed to a string via converting the bytes into a string.

  • Rather useful for unpacking JSON object tidyjson

  • Tidyjson is useful if the nest list has multiple elements with the same names. However,for single and small bits of information, direct subsetting using [[ ]] will be the easiest.

  • A function used to extract lat/lng information for the origin and destination of the directions response, using tidyjson.

    extracting_Origin_End = function(response_Text)
{   ##This is to illustrate how to get the lat/lng using the tidyjson format.
        ## Consider the tbl_json object as a variable data frame
        ## where dimensions are constantly changed by functions such as
        ## spread, stack
        
        
    require(tidyjson)
    require(dplyr)

    # Extracting direction markers for start: 
    directions_Markers_Start =response_Text %>% as.tbl_json %>% 
        enter_object("routes") %>% gather_array %>%
        enter_object("legs") %>% gather_array %>%
        spread_values(
            address = jstring("start_address")
        ) %>% enter_object("start_location")%>%
        spread_values(
            lat = jnumber("lat"),
            lng = jnumber("lng")
        ) %>% select(address, lat,lng)%>% 
        tbl_df
    
    directions_Markers_End = response_Text %>% as.tbl_json %>% 
        enter_object("routes") %>% gather_array %>%
        enter_object("legs") %>% gather_array %>%
        spread_values(
            address = jstring("end_address")
        ) %>% enter_object("end_location")%>%
        spread_values(
            lat = jnumber("lat"),
            lng = jnumber("lng")
        ) %>% select(address, lat,lng)%>% 
        tbl_df 
        
        
    directions_Markers = rbind(directions_Markers_Start,directions_Markers_End)
    return(directions_Markers)
}
  • Decoding Polyline Function borrowed:
# Custom decode function
# Taken from http://s4rdd.blogspot.com
# /2012/12/google-maps-api-decoding-polylines-for.html

decodeLine <- function(encoded){
  require(bitops)

  vlen <- nchar(encoded)
  vindex <- 0
  varray <- NULL
  vlat <- 0
  vlng <- 0

  while(vindex < vlen){
    vb <- NULL
    vshift <- 0
    vresult <- 0
    repeat{
      if(vindex + 1 <= vlen){
        vindex <- vindex + 1
        vb <- as.integer(charToRaw(substr(encoded, vindex, vindex))) - 63  
      }

      vresult <- bitOr(vresult, bitShiftL(bitAnd(vb, 31), vshift))
      vshift <- vshift + 5
      if(vb < 32) break
    }

    dlat <- ifelse(
      bitAnd(vresult, 1)
      , -(bitShiftR(vresult, 1)+1)
      , bitShiftR(vresult, 1)
    )
    vlat <- vlat + dlat

    vshift <- 0
    vresult <- 0
    repeat{
      if(vindex + 1 <= vlen) {
        vindex <- vindex+1
        vb <- as.integer(charToRaw(substr(encoded, vindex, vindex))) - 63        
      }

      vresult <- bitOr(vresult, bitShiftL(bitAnd(vb, 31), vshift))
      vshift <- vshift + 5
      if(vb < 32) break
    }

    dlng <- ifelse(
      bitAnd(vresult, 1)
      , -(bitShiftR(vresult, 1)+1)
      , bitShiftR(vresult, 1)
    )
    vlng <- vlng + dlng

    varray <- rbind(varray, c(vlat * 1e-5, vlng * 1e-5))
  }
  coords <- data.frame(varray)
  names(coords) <- c("lat", "lon")
  coords
}

    # Setting up for URL requests
    work_Lat = directions_Markers$lat[[1]]
    work_Lng = directions_Markers$lng[[1]]
    home_Lat = directions_Markers$lat[[2]]
    home_Lng = directions_Markers$lng[[2]]
    keyword = "point+of+interest"
    ## circular radius in meters
    radius = 2000
    
    
    #function to extract rawData:
    place_Raw_data = function(lat, lng, keyword, radius, api_Key)
    {
        request = paste(host,"/place/nearbysearch/json",
        "?location=",lat,",",lng,"&radius=",
        radius,"&keyword=",keyword, "&key=",
        api_Key,sep="")
        
        raw = jsonlite::fromJSON(content(
                GET(request),"text"
            ))
        
    }
    
    # Getting Raw Data
    poi_Work_Raw= place_Raw_data(work_Lat, work_Lng,
                            keyword, radius, api_Key)
    poi_Home_Raw = place_Raw_data(home_Lat, home_Lng,
                            keyword, radius, api_Key)
    
    # Function to format Raw Data into organized DF:
    
    organizePlaceDF= function(raw_Data)
    {
        lat_Lng = raw_Data$results$geometry$location
        names = as.vector(unlist(raw_Data$results$name))
        icon = as.vector(unlist(raw_Data$results$icon))
        rating = as.vector(unlist(raw_Data$results$rating))
        organized_Data = cbind(lat_Lng,rating,icon,names)
        organized_Data
    }
    
    
    # getting DF
    home_Df = organizePlaceDF(poi_Home_Raw)
    work_Df = organizePlaceDF(poi_Work_Raw)
    place_Df = rbind(home_Df,work_Df)
    
    #setting up Icons:
    place_Icons <- icons(
      iconUrl = place_Df$icon,
      iconWidth = 20, iconHeight = 20,
      iconAnchorX = 0, iconAnchorY =0
    )
    
    #setting up label contents:
    content =list()
    for(i in 1:length(place_Df$icon))
    {
        content_Name= paste("name:",
            place_Df$names[[i]],"<br>")
        
        content_Rating= paste("rating:",
            place_Df$rating[[i]],"<br>")
        
        content[[i]] = 
            paste(content_Name, content_Rating,
                  sep="<br>")
        
    }
    
    
    # adding the locations onto the map using google Icons
    example2_Map = addMarkers(example2_Map, lat=place_Df$lat, 
                    lng=place_Df$lng,icon=place_Icons,
                    popup=as.vector(content))
    
    
    
     example2_Map

Mini-Project: Plotting Origin,Destination Pairs

Description:

  • Extract 100 origin/destination city pairs. Where the origin are random cities in Alberta and the destination are cities outside of Alberta but inside Canada.
    • To ensure reproducibility, the randomly selected origin/destination pairs are stored under the csv file progress.csv.

  • Store the addresses for origin/destination pairs along with their lat/long as well as route distance, time, average speed and straight line distance into a csv file.

  • Plot the origin/destination pairs with their route onto a map.

Setting up List of Cities

  • List of cities copied into a text document named list of cities, needs reformatting to extract city name and province.
    ## Sample city raw format: 1: 100 Mile House, British Columbia 

    raw_Citys = read.table("List of Cities.txt",header = TRUE, sep ="\n")

    ## getting rid of numbers:
    
    raw_Citys = lapply(raw_Citys, function(x){
        gsub(pattern = "[0-9]+:", "",x)
    })
    
    raw_Citys = unlist(raw_Citys)
    
    
    ## Separating into city and province
    citys = list()
    province = list()
    for(i in 1: length(raw_Citys)){
        separated = unlist( strsplit(raw_Citys[[i]],",") )
        citys[[i]] = gsub(" ","",separated[1])
        province[[i]] = gsub(" ","",separated[2])
        
    }
    
    raw_Citys_DF = data.frame(city=unlist(citys),
                    province=unlist(province))

    rm(list = setdiff(ls(),c("raw_Citys_DF")))

Getting Direction information

    api_Key = "AIzaSyBGTs-gZCbyP8n0Hvw_VZ76Z6YrST1DNa8"
    host = "https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api"
  • A function that uses the google maps API to find lat/lng for the cities.
## takes lists containing: (orig_City, orig_Province,
##  dest_city,dest_provice) and a api_Key
##  assume that the lists are matching and same length

## return a data frame containing lat,lng, route information

    lat_Lng = function(orig_city,orig_province,
                       dest_city,dest_province,
                        api_Key){
        
        ##libraries needed
        require(jsonlite)
        require(httr)
        
        
        ## some google request information
        host = "https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api"
        service = "/directions/json"
        
        
        ## lists to fill for a data frame
        orig_lat = list()
        orig_lng = list()
        orig_address = list()
        dest_lat = list()
        dest_lng = list()
        dest_address = list()
        polyline = list()
        time_text = list()
        time_value = list()
        distance_text = list()
        distance_value = list()
        
        
        ##looping through list and get the lat/lng
        for( i in 1:length(orig_city)){
            
            ## Getting names of city and province
            origin = paste(orig_city[[i]],orig_province[[i]],sep=",")
            origin = gsub(" ", "+",origin)
            dest = paste(dest_city[[i]],dest_province[[i]],sep=",")
            dest = gsub(" ", "+", dest)
            
            ##formatting api request
            directions_Request = paste(host, service,"?origin=",origin,
                               "&destination=",dest,
                               "&key=",api_Key,sep ="")
            
            ## getting nested response list
            raw = GET(directions_Request)
            
            directions_Response = jsonlite::fromJSON(
                content(raw,"text")
            )
            
            ##  Just to check if response is ok
            if(directions_Response$status != "Ok")
                warnings("Request not successful")
            
            
            
            ##geting lat and lng for origin and destination
            
            route_info = directions_Response$routes$legs[[1]]
            
            start_df = route_info[["start_location"]]
            ## a bit truncated
            orig_lat[[i]] = start_df$lat
            orig_lng[[i]] = start_df$lng
            orig_address[[i]] = route_info$start_address
            
            end_df = route_info[["end_location"]]
            dest_lat[[i]] = end_df$lat
            dest_lng[[i]]= end_df$lng
            dest_address[[i]] = route_info$end_address
            
            
            ##getting time, distance info
            time_value[[i]] = route_info$duration$value
            time_text[[i]] = route_info$duration$text
            distance_text[[i]] = route_info$distance$text
            distance_value[[i]] = route_info$distance$value
            
            ##route for map:
            polyline[[i]] = directions_Response$routes$overview_polyline[["points"]]
        }
        
        
        ##making the data frame
        
        df = data.frame(orig_address = unlist(orig_address),
                orig_lat =unlist(orig_lat),
                orig_lng = unlist(orig_lng),
                dest_address = unlist(dest_address),
                dest_lat = unlist(dest_lat),
                dest_lng = unlist(dest_lng),
                time_text = unlist(time_text),
                time_value = unlist(time_value),
                distance_text = unlist(distance_text),
                distance_value = unlist(distance_value),
                polyline = unlist(polyline)
            
        )
        return(df)
        
    }

Calculating Straight Line Distance in km:

  • Internet recommended to use geosphere package.
    rm(list = ls())
    require(geosphere)
    progress_DF = read.table("progess2.csv", header=TRUE,sep=",", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
    
    ## calculating the straight line distance 
    ## for each origin/dest pair
    straight_Dis = list()
    for( i in 1:dim(progress_DF)[1]){
        p1 = as.numeric( c(progress_DF$orig_lng[[i]],progress_DF$orig_lat[[i]]) )
        p2 = as.numeric( c(progress_DF$dest_lng[[i]],progress_DF$dest_lat[[i]]) )
        
        straight_Dis[[i]] = geosphere::distVincentyEllipsoid(p1,p2)/1000
    }
    
    progress_DF = cbind(progress_DF, straight_dis = unlist(straight_Dis))

Decoding polylines:

  • Decoding Polyline Function copied from here

  • More info on polylines

# Custom decode function
# Taken from http://s4rdd.blogspot.com
# /2012/12/google-maps-api-decoding-polylines-for.html

decodeLine <- function(encoded){
  require(bitops)

  vlen <- nchar(encoded)
  vindex <- 0
  varray <- NULL
  vlat <- 0
  vlng <- 0

  while(vindex < vlen){
    vb <- NULL
    vshift <- 0
    vresult <- 0
    repeat{
      if(vindex + 1 <= vlen){
        vindex <- vindex + 1
        vb <- as.integer(charToRaw(substr(encoded, vindex, vindex))) - 63  
      }

      vresult <- bitOr(vresult, bitShiftL(bitAnd(vb, 31), vshift))
      vshift <- vshift + 5
      if(vb < 32) break
    }

    dlat <- ifelse(
      bitAnd(vresult, 1)
      , -(bitShiftR(vresult, 1)+1)
      , bitShiftR(vresult, 1)
    )
    vlat <- vlat + dlat

    vshift <- 0
    vresult <- 0
    repeat{
      if(vindex + 1 <= vlen) {
        vindex <- vindex+1
        vb <- as.integer(charToRaw(substr(encoded, vindex, vindex))) - 63        
      }

      vresult <- bitOr(vresult, bitShiftL(bitAnd(vb, 31), vshift))
      vshift <- vshift + 5
      if(vb < 32) break
    }

    dlng <- ifelse(
      bitAnd(vresult, 1)
      , -(bitShiftR(vresult, 1)+1)
      , bitShiftR(vresult, 1)
    )
    vlng <- vlng + dlng

    varray <- rbind(varray, c(vlat * 1e-5, vlng * 1e-5))
  }
  coords <- data.frame(varray)
  names(coords) <- c("lat", "lon")
  coords
}

Setting up Basic Map

    library(leaflet)
    library(htmltools)
    
    ##calculating max/min lat and lng for the bounding box.
    lat = append(progress_DF$orig_lat, progress_DF$dest_lat)
    min_Lat = min(lat)
    max_Lat = max(lat)
   
    lng = append(progress_DF$dest_lng, progress_DF$orig_lng)
    min_Lng = min(lng)
    max_Lng = max(lng)

    #   Making Icons
    orig = makeAwesomeIcon(markerColor="red", iconColor="yellow")
    
    # adding popup labels
    popup = function(address){
        list = lapply( address, function(x){
            split = unlist( strsplit(x, ",") )
            city = paste("city:", split[1])
            province = paste("province: ", split[2])
            country = paste("country: ", split[3])
            out = paste(city, province, country, sep = "<br/>")
        })
        
        return( as.character(list) )
    }
  
    
   
    ##  loading basic map. 
    map = leaflet() %>%
        addProviderTiles(provider="OpenStreetMap.Mapnik") %>%
        fitBounds(max_Lng,max_Lat,min_Lng,max_Lat) %>%
    ##  adding markers
        addAwesomeMarkers(lng=progress_DF$orig_lng,
                   lat=progress_DF$orig_lat,
                   icon=orig,
                   popup = popup(progress_DF$orig_address)) %>%
        addMarkers(lng=progress_DF$dest_lng,
                   lat=progress_DF$dest_lat) %>%
     ##  Adding legend: 
        addLegend(position = "topright", 
            labels = c("origin","destination"),
            color = c("Red","Blue"), layerId = "legends")
    ## adding Polyline
      
    for(i in 1: length(progress_DF$polyline)){
        df = decodeLine(as.character(progress_DF$polyline[[i]]))
        
        map = map %>%
            addPolylines(lng=df$lon,lat=df$lat, color = "yellow")
    }
